- OS_impl_timebase_internal_record_t: needed to see the types of members accessed (sigset and reset_flag) and whether those members or the record type are declared const; impl->reset_flag is written, so this determines if impl must be a non-const pointer.
- OS_timebase_internal_record_t: needed to see the types of nominal_interval_time and nominal_start_time and whether the record (or those members) are const; timebase is only read in the function so this tells if it can be a pointer to const.
- OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET (macro): determines how the token is converted into a pointer (what pointer type/result it yields). If the macro yields a non-const pointer type or performs casts, that affects whether the local pointer can/should be declared const.
- OS_impl_timebase_table and OS_timebase_table: the declared types of the table objects can influence the pointer type returned by OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET (e.g., pointer-to-const vs pointer-to-non-const).
- OS_ObjectIdGetById: the prototype/signature is needed to confirm the token type produced and any const-related behavior of the API that might constrain pointer constness (and to ensure token use is correct).
- OS_object_token_t: type of token used by OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET; needed to understand indexing and any constness constraints coming from token-to-pointer conversion.
- OS_ObjectIndexFromToken: this helper is referenced in the static call graph and may be used by OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET; its prototype/behavior can affect the resulting pointer type and const-qualification.
- sigwait: standard function prototype is required to confirm its parameter type (const sigset_t *) so we know whether passing &impl->sigset is compatible and whether the callee expects a const-qualified pointer.
- sigset_t: type of impl->sigset member; needed to verify that the member has the expected type and whether it is declared const or not (affects whether taking its address yields a pointer-to-const).

These symbols together let the next analyst determine whether the local pointers (impl, timebase, and the pointer passed to sigwait) could/should be declared with const-qualified target types under MISRA guidance, and whether any macros or API signatures force non-const pointers.
